      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are looking a bit weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kind of yellow, but the top ones look okay for now. any idea what's going on? and how do i fix the soil if i need to?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing lower leaves on your tomato plants, especially when the top ones are still looking healthy, is a classic sign of a few things, like a nutrient deficiency, which is often the case when the plant is trying to hoard resources for the new growth at the top. It's a very common issue, and it's almost always related to how the soil is behaving, which is where the real work needs to happen.\n\nIf the yellowing is starting from the bottom and moving up, it often points toward a mobile nutrient deficiency, like nitrogen. You can try a balanced, slow-release fertilizer, but if you suspect a specific issue, a quick soil test is the best way to know exactly what your tomatoes are craving.\n\nAs for fixing the soil, if it's compacted or draining poorly, you might need to amend it. Incorporating some aged compost is usually the go-to fix; it improves drainage while slowly feeding the roots. If the soil is too acidic or alkaline, you might need to adjust that with lime or sulfur, depending on what your test tells you.\n\nIt's a bit like trying to get a proper meal cooked for a whole crew of hungry, picky little green things—the soil needs",
      "source": "target",
