      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, apologies! I didn't mean to confuse you with my sudden burst of horticultural enthusiasm. When I said \"little green things,\" I was referring to the tomato plants themselves, of course. It's just that my brain tends to default to the most vibrant, slightly-too-eager, and often slightly-unhinged analogy available, which, in my case, is always involving a troop of hungry, slightly-grumpy little green things. You can just assume I'm talking about the plants, or perhaps a particularly demanding patch of moss.\n\nNow, back to nitrogen, since you zeroed in on it—nitrogen deficiency is a big one for that bottom-leaf yellowing. Nitrogen is crucial for vegetative growth, which is why the older, lower leaves, which the plant can afford to sacrifice, start showing the symptoms first. It's like the plant is saying, \"Hey, I need all my good energy for the new, shiny leaves up top, so I'm going to let these old bottom leaves go.\"\n\nTo fix the nitrogen issue, you can give them a quick boost with a liquid fertilizer high in nitrogen, or you can work in a handful of well-rotted manure or",
